  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(32) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "In those days.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—As a vassal and ally of Assyria (see Notes on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 9:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Jehu drew upon himself the active hostility of Hazael. (See Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 8:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) Schröder remarks that it was quite natural for the Israelite sovereign to “throw himself into the arms of distant Assyria, in order to get protection against his immediate neighbour Syria, Israel’s hereditary foe.” Comp. the similar conduct of Ahaz as against Pekah and Rezin (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 16:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). From the point of view of the sacred writer, this verse states the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "consequence",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Jehu’s neglect of “walking in Jehovah’s instruction with all his heart” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 10:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Lord began.—Through Hazael and the Syrians. (Comp. Isaiah 7:17; Isaiah 7:20; Isaiah 10:5-6.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The Lord began.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Through Hazael and the Syrians. (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 7:17",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 7:20",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 10:5-6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To cut Israel short.—Literally, to cut off in Israel—i.e., to cut off part after part of Israelite territory. (The verb means to cut off the extremities, Proverbs 26:6.) This refers to the conquests of Hazael. The Targum explains, “The wrath of the Lord began to be strong against Israel;” and the Vulg. has, “tædere super Israel.” Thenius conjectures from this that we should read, “to be wrathful with Israel;” but the construction would not then be usual.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "To cut Israel short.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "to cut off in Israel—i.e.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", to cut off part after part of Israelite territory. (The verb means ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "to cut off the extremities",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 26:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) This refers to the conquests of Hazael. The Targum explains, “The wrath of the Lord began to be strong against Israel;” and the Vulg. has, “tædere super Israel.” Thenius conjectures from this that we should read, “to be wrathful with Israel;” but the construction would not then be usual.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In all the coasts.—Rather, on the whole border—scil., conterminous with Syria.",
