        "text": "Verse 32.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "In those days the Lord began to out Israel short.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It is certainly not stated in direct terms that the ill success of Jehu's foreign wars was a punishment on him for his continued maintenance of the calf-idolatry; but the juxtaposition of vers. 31 and 32 naturally raises the idea, and constitutes a strong presumption that it was in the writer's mind. The \"theocracy\" under the kings was carried on mainly, as the writer of Chronicles clearly saw, by the bestowal of worldly prosperity and military success on good kings, and the accumulation of misfortunes and military disasters on bad ones (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:5-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 13:4-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:2-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 15:2-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 17:3-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". etc.). By \"cutting Israel short\" - literally, \"cutting off in Israel\" - is probably meant the conquest of certain portions of the territory. Hazael resumed the war which Benhadad had so long waged, and gained numerous successes. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And Hazael smote them in all the coasts of Israel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "along their whole frontier",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Bahr). The frontier intended is, of course, that on the north and east, where the Israelite territory was conterminous with that of Syria. 2 Kings 10:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
